Ah — that changes things. If your base image is Ubuntu, then dnf will never work. You need to use apt, not dnf.


---

✅ Correct fix for Ubuntu-based Dockerfiles

In all Dockerfiles that include ncm, add:

RUN apt-get update && \
    apt-get install -y \
        libcjson-dev \
        libcjson1 \
    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*


---

🔍 Why both packages?

libcjson1 → runtime library (libcjson.so)

libcjson-dev → headers (only needed if compiling, but safe to include)


If you're not compiling inside container, you can reduce to:

RUN apt-get update && \
    apt-get install -y libcjson1 && \
    rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*


---

🧪 Verify inside container

After build:

ldd /path/to/ncm.xcg | grep cjson

Expected:

libcjson.so.1 => /usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libcjson.so.1


---

⚠️ If apt is NOT available

Some minimal Ubuntu images (like scratch-based or stripped ones) may not have package repos configured.

Then fallback to your earlier approach:

Manual copy (Ubuntu paths differ!)

Instead of /lib64, use:

COPY libcjson/ /usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/

For ARM:

COPY libcjson/ /usr/lib/aarch64-linux-gnu/

Then:

RUN ldconfig


---

🚨 Architecture handling (important in your case)

Since you mentioned ACA (ARM):

x86 → /usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/

ARM → /usr/lib/aarch64-linux-gnu/


Mixing these will break the container.


---

🔥 Best practice (strongly recommended)

Instead of modifying 15+ Dockerfiles:

👉 Create a base Ubuntu image with libcjson preinstalled

FROM ubuntu:22.04

RUN apt-get update && \
    apt-get install -y libcjson1 && \
    rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

Then update all Dockerfiles:

FROM your-custom-ubuntu-base


---

💡 Quick decision guide

Situation	Best approach

Internet access + apt works	✅ apt install libcjson1
Air-gapped	✅ Manual .so copy
Many Dockerfiles	✅ Custom base image



